{"candidates": [{"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness strictly beats SC iff base error e is in the majority-fragile zone 1/(k+1) < e < 1/2 AND critic precision P > 1/2 AND recall R > 0; harness loses (strictly underperforms SC) when P < 1/2 because false flags flip more correct majorities than true flags fix broken ones.\", \"mechanism\": \"SC majority is wrong iff at least ceil(k/2) candidates err. In the fragile zone this probability is nonzero but below 1/2, so SC is sometimes wrong. Harness fixes a broken majority only when the critic flags enough error candidates to prevent the wrong answer from surviving (needs R high enough to catch >1 error in a broken batch). Harness breaks a correct majority when the critic false-flags enough correct candidates to flip the plurality to a wrong answer; this happens with probability proportional to (1-P)/e. Net gain = P_fix * P(SC wrong) - P_break * P(SC right). When P < 1/2 the false-flag rate exceeds the true-flag rate, so P_break dominates and harness nets negative.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"k=5, e in (0.17, 0.50), P in (0.5, 1.0), R in (0, 1]\", \"k=3, e in (0.25, 0.50), P in (0.5, 1.0)\", \"k=7, e in (0.125, 0.50), P in (0.5, 1.0)\", \"counterexample regime P < 0.5 where harness strictly loses to SC\"], \"excludes\": [\"e < 1/(k+1): SC already near ceiling, no room to improve\", \"e >= 1/2: SC already failing majority, harness cannot reliably recover\", \"question-conditional critic calibration that varies P per item\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.30, P=0.7, R=0.8: harness accuracy equals SC accuracy (tie, no strict gain) despite being inside the predicted winning zone\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.30, P=0.3, R=0.9: harness accuracy strictly exceeds SC (gain despite P < 1/2, contradicting the false-flag loss prediction)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.05, P=0.9, R=0.9: harness strictly beats SC (gain outside the fragile zone, contradicting the necessary-condition claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.45, P=0.9, R=0.2: harness strictly beats SC by more than 5 points (gain with recall too low to catch enough errors in a broken majority)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the fixed-regime generalization of the observed data. The v4-flash easy result (e=0.033, P=0.333) falls outside the fragile zone AND has P < 1/2, so the prediction is no gain — matching the tie. The v4-pro hard result (e=0.01, P=0.125) is deep in the ceiling regime, so no gain — matching. The decisive experiment targets the fragile zone with controlled P above and below 1/2. Budget: 60 items * (5 candidates + 5 critiques + 5 re-votes) * ~600 tokens/call = ~180k tokens, plus answer-key evaluation ~20k, well within 300k.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "3a28bc3e8bde28be2af04bc4e23b5753948be3c6b53c7580e5edbc8fceab68da", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "862de34bced36d488ac299f984c270812db349a12e50b3acf126462c0be93e72", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "ba687c5f145e404c53a84549cf366e0b6e0106eec67404c07231357fed09e672", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.9}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed (e, P, R, k) regime is sufficient to predict strict harness advantage; harness strictly beats SC only when the critic is question-adaptive such that its per-item flagging accuracy exceeds a threshold tied to that item's candidate error count, and otherwise the critic's fixed P/R can either help or hurt depending on question-difficulty alignment.\", \"mechanism\": \"Items are heterogeneous: each question q has a latent difficulty producing an error-count m_q in {0, ..., k}. A fixed-P/R critic applies the same flagging behavior to every q, but the net effect depends on m_q. For items where m_q >= ceil(k/2) (broken majority), the critic needs high recall on that specific item. For items where m_q < ceil(k/2) (correct majority), the critic needs high precision on that specific item. A critic with fixed aggregate P, R can have high P on easy items and low P on hard items (or vice versa), so the aggregate values do not determine the outcome. Harness strictly beats SC only when per-item critic accuracy is calibrated to the per-item error regime: high R on broken-majority items AND high P on correct-majority items. The observed v4-pro hard data (P=0.125, R=1.0, net=0) is consistent because the 1 item with an error had R=1.0 but the low P did not matter since all other items had m_q=0 (nothing to false-flag that mattered).\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"per-item critic calibration as the key variable\", \"fixed-P/R critics acting on heterogeneous question pools\", \"decomposing net gain into per-item contributions conditional on m_q\"], \"excludes\": [\"any prediction from aggregate P, R alone\", \"homogeneous-question pools where all items share the same m_q\", \"regimes where the critic has access to the answer key\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Two experiments with identical aggregate (e=0.30, P=0.7, R=0.8, k=5) but different per-item critic calibration produce the same harness-vs-SC gap (contradicting the claim that calibration, not aggregate values, determines the outcome)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with perfect per-item calibration (R=1 on broken-majority items, P=1 on correct-majority items) fails to strictly beat SC at e=0.30, k=5 (contradicting the sufficiency claim)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"A critic with aggregate P=0.8, R=0.8 at e=0.30, k=5 strictly beats SC on one question set but strictly loses to SC on another with the same aggregate statistics (directly confirming per-item heterogeneity dominates)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This supersedes the fixed-regime candidate by arguing that the observed null results are not explained by aggregate P/R alone but by the alignment between per-item critic behavior and per-item error structure. The decisive experiment must hold aggregate P/R approximately fixed while varying per-item calibration — achievable by sorting questions by difficulty and using two critic variants (one difficulty-correlated, one anti-correlated). Budget: 60 items * 2 critic variants * (5 candidates + 5 critiques + 5 re-votes) * ~500 tokens = ~300k tokens, at the budget boundary. If budget is tight, reduce to 40 items.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "c9386a6c7b3038d7ebaf9f80aed2b6bfd17ad2be03ed64556d0173f0d0085495", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "30e483eb494067d8323a796b7e319a77a3abce4c45ba08a487df2b6838e5082b", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.75}, {"content": "{\"claim\": \"Harness can strictly beat SC even at very low base error e (outside the fragile zone) provided the critic has near-perfect precision and the question pool contains at least one item where SC fails due to a bare-majority error cluster; the critical variable is not average e but the tail probability of a wrong-majority event times the critic's ability to catch it without collateral damage.\", \"mechanism\": \"SC fails only on items where >= ceil(k/2) candidates are wrong. Even at e=0.05 with k=5, the probability of 3+ errors in a batch is C(5,3)*0.05^3*0.95^2 + ... ~= 1.2%. Over 100+ items this produces measurable SC failures. If the critic has P=1.0 (zero false flags) and R>0, then every flagged item is a true error, so filtering can only help: it removes errors from broken majorities (potentially fixing them) and never damages correct majorities. The net gain is strictly positive whenever there exists at least one broken-majority item AND the critic flags at least one error candidate in that batch. The observed v4-flash data (P=0.333) does not refute this because P was far below 1.0; the false flags erased the gains. The v4-pro hard data (e=0.01) had at most 1 broken-majority item in 20 questions, yielding no measurable gap.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"P=1.0 (perfect precision), any R>0, any e>0, large question pool (n>=100)\", \"regimes where SC ceiling is not truly reached because rare broken majorities exist\", \"counterexample: P < 1.0 at low e where false flags erase the rare gains\"], \"excludes\": [\"P < 1.0 with small n (false-flag noise dominates)\", \"e so low that no broken-majority event occurs in the sample\", \"critic with access to answer key (trivial P=1, R=1)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.05, P=1.0, R=0.5, n=100: harness does NOT strictly beat SC (no gain despite perfect precision and at least one broken-majority item)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.05, P=0.95, R=0.5, n=100: harness strictly beats SC by the same margin as P=1.0 (false flags at P=0.95 cause zero damage, contradicting the claim that P<1.0 erodes gains)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}, {\"case\": \"At k=5, e=0.05, P=1.0, R=1.0, n=100: SC and harness tie at 1.00 (no broken-majority event occurs, contradicting the predicted 1.2% event rate)\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This is the atypical candidate: it claims the fragile-zone boundary is not a necessary condition because rare tail events at low e can still produce SC failures that a perfect-precision critic can fix. The decisive experiment requires a large pool (n>=100) to observe the rare events and a critic architecture that achieves near-perfect precision (e.g., a critic that only flags when it assigns >0.95 probability of error). Budget: 100 items * (5 candidates + 5 critiques + 5 re-votes) * ~500 tokens = ~250k tokens, within budget. The counterexample-first stance is honored by the P=0.95 forbidden case: if false flags at 5% cause zero damage, the P=1.0 sufficiency claim is weakened.\"}", "refs": [{"target": "3a28bc3e8bde28be2af04bc4e23b5753948be3c6b53c7580e5edbc8fceab68da", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "862de34bced36d488ac299f984c270812db349a12e50b3acf126462c0be93e72", "role": "dependence"}, {"target": "74fde5320d6c79520ea82d22a3e0c25a5ecc8e0cb50c3197058c5a3b0ecd2845", "role": "mention"}, {"target": "495c5963dafbd26bf2aa1838491e8428005b9a54825f21a8df1e5ead37908e7a", "role": "dependence"}], "typicality": 0.3}]}